  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Generative Artificial Intelligence (GenAI) broadly refers to a class of AI models that produce new content in the form of text, video, images, or other media in response to prompts.",
    "For example, GenAI systems can write convincing documents, create digital art, compose music, engage and debate with humans, and produce software.",
    "Although GenAI techniques have been around for some time (Benbya et al., 2020 (Benbya et al.,, 2021)), the recent public release of tools such as ChatGPT, GitHub Copilot, and DALL-E followed by Google's Bard and Microsoft's Bing have brought the potential of such solutions to the forefront.",
    "Contemporary GenAI systems have attracted significant attention from diverse stakeholders and generated intense debates about GenAI impact on business and society.",
    "1 The term \"knowledge work\" was first introduced by Peter Drucker in the 1960s as being any work that requires mental rather than physical power."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Although GenAI techniques have been around for some time (Benbya et al., 2020 (Benbya et al.,, 2021)), the recent public release of tools such as ChatGPT, GitHub Copilot, and DALL-E followed by Google's Bard and Microsoft's Bing have brought the potential of such solutions to the forefront."
